As the People’s Democratic Party, the country’s main opposition party, grapples with questions about its decline and future in national politics, the presidency has said Nigerians must be surprised reading a statement issued by them, assuming the role of spokesmen for President Muhammadu Buhari. Presidential spokesman, Garba Shehu wondered what business the opposition had in talking about alleged distance between President Buhari and the ruling All Progressives Congress (APC). He pointed out that the PDP represents the single biggest obstacle to good governance and change that the country needs, that the people are yearning for. According to him, “Both self-respect and sound political judgement demand that the party take an introspective look at itself after two successive defeats in national elections, asking what went wrong and how to fix its battered image. ”They need to go back to the people, in towns and villages, to know what the people want and what the country needs. Instead of doing that, they are taking roles for themselves that are not mandated by law, morality or political gamesmanship. ”What business do they have issuing a statement on the love or the lack of it between the president and his party? This is not why they lost elections. The party needs a reboot that aligns with current national mood and aspirations, to focus on their grim future after two successive defeats. It is the issue they need to focus on if they are to be taken as a serious opposition party again. ”A tough task awaits anyone leading a party with nothing to offer to contemporary Nigerians but corruption, misgovernance and division. ”As for the APC, the geographical expansion of the party is nothing short of a testimony to the rosy future that lies ahead. The party has come to stay, and the president and the country will ensure that this is achieved, he added.